# 1 Introduction {#1-introduction}

## 1.1 Outline of Automated Vehicles {#1.1-outline-of-automated-vehicles}

As expressed in *Software System of Autonomous Vehicles: Architecture, Network and OS,* Autonomous vehicles (AVs) are designed to operate without human intervention, categorized into five levels of autonomy. Lower levels (0-3) include Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS) that aid with emergency braking and parallel parking, while higher levels (4-5) strive for full automation through advanced machine intelligence and data integration. 

Unlike traditional computing systems, AVs rely on multiple Electronic Computing Units (ECUs) that manage different vehicle functions such as vision, radar, steering, and braking. Future designs aim to consolidate these components into a more streamlined architecture, reducing complexity and improving performance.

The AV industry is rapidly evolving, with major automotive and technology companies investing in research and development. In the coming years, fully automated vehicles will be more readily available to day-to-day consumers. However, the industry is still in its early stages and therefore lacks the regulations and standards that are present in more established fields such as automation within the aerospace industry.

## 

## 1.2 Project Scope {#1.2-project-scope}

The current scope of the project refers to the creation and running of onboard software used to allow an AV to fully self-drive. The project will consist of a simulation of the sensors and will not be implemented into a test vehicle, but rather be the first release of many to incrementally build a complete mission-critical real-time embedded system. An Internet of Things (IoT) network will be used to allow an interconnection between all the embedded systems within the AV. The devices will be connected via an internal bus to ensure fast and accurate cross-communication with each device. An IoT Engine will be used to process information and make decisions which will be passed to the Vehicle Control System (VCS) for full self-driving. The driver will receive status updates on the current state of the system and will be able to input commands via the steering wheel in case of emergencies. The IoT Engine will support full Cloud uploading and downloading of both software updates and vehicle data for further analysis by the manufacturer. 

## 

## 1.3 Project Management {#1.3-project-management}

The project management was conducted in an agile manner using an iterative process to achieve all of our goals, specifically Scrum. Scrum is an agile management framework designed for projects to be done collaboratively amongst a team while still prioritizing efficiency. Biweekly, we elected a new Scrum leader to “coordinate project activities, align these with business objectives, and break down projects into smaller pieces” (Indeed Editorial Team). This process allowed us to break the project into manageable tasks, delivering incremental results. 

Weekly meetings outside of instruction were conducted to track progress, align efforts, and identify where key focuses were needed. These meetings encourage constant communication between team members, ensuring each member is aware of their responsibilities. The Scrum leader took the initiative to generate sprint retrospectives where the team reflected on the previous sprint to identify ways of improving and ensuring accountability among team members.

The agile approach fits best for the needs of the project because, with software, we want to work closely with the customer and create a project they want before sinking too much time into the deliverables. This iterative approach allows the team to ensure what features should be prioritized. Likewise, with a small team such as The Luminary Collective, creating time to verify which task each member is completing and the progress of those tasks was effective in achieving the scope of the project.

# 2 Architecture  {#2-architecture}

Fig 1\. Functional Architecture

## 2.1 Functional Architecture {#2.1-functional-architecture}

The system will be designed with a modular IoT-based architecture integrating the following key components: Sensors, Localization, Perception, Planning, IoT Engine, Vehicle Control System (VCS), System Management, Technical Interface, Driver Intervention, and Cloud Connectivity. The Sensor Module will aggregate data from LiDAR, RGB cameras, radar, and ultrasonic sensors to construct an accurate environmental model. The Localization Module will use GPS, IMU, and map-based data to determine the vehicle’s precise position. The Perception Module will analyze sensor data to detect and classify objects, road conditions, and obstacles, while the Planning Module will generate optimized paths for navigation and decision-making. The IoT Engine will process data and determine necessary lane correction or maneuvering actions. The VCS will handle lane maintenance, trajectory control, and collision avoidance to execute these commands. The System Management Module will oversee diagnostics, resource allocation, and fail-safe operations to enhance system reliability. A Technical Interface will ensure that data logs within the system management unit are accessible locally. The Human Intervention Module will allow for emergency human input in cases of self-driving failure or errors. Lastly, Cloud Connectivity will facilitate remote diagnostics, data logging, and over-the-air updates, ensuring that the system is up-to-date and adaptable.

## 2.2 Functionality {#2.2-functionality}

The following section will detail the functionality of the system’s architecture and the data flow used to achieve full self-driving capabilities.

### 2.2.1 Sensors {#2.2.1-sensors}

The sensor module is a collective of individual sensors that each collect different types of data that are sent into both the localization and perception modules. The sensors include LiDAR, RGB cameras, radar, ultrasonic sensors, GPS, Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU), and map-based data. The sensors feed data into both the localization and perception modules.

![][image1]

### 2.2.2 Localization {#2.2.2-localization}

The localization module interprets the data collected from the sensor inputs and determines precisely where the vehicle is within the space in a real-time environment. This information is formulated by taking the sensor data such as GPS coordinates and image data to develop a concrete position within real space for navigation and lane correction. The localization module will feed its data, the computed vehicle position, directly to the planning module in real time, which will then propose action for the VCS if needed.

### 2.2.3 Perception {#2.2.3-perception}

The perception module intercepts the raw data collected by the sensors to identify objects, road rights, lane markings, pedestrians, and other vehicles. It employs advanced image recognition and deep learning algorithms to classify these elements, allowing the planning module to make informed decisions. This module is crucial for detecting obstacles, recognizing traffic signals, and the movement of other road users. The data from this module is sent directly to the planning module.

### 2.2.4 Planning {#2.2.4-planning}

The planning module is responsible for determining the optimal driving path by analyzing data from the localization and perception modules. It takes into account road curvature, traffic density, land constraints, and potential hazards to generate safe and efficient navigation decisions. The planning system updates its calculations at each clock cycle with data from the localization and perception module to adapt to road conditions ensuring smooth and responsive vehicle movement. The planning module will send instructions to the VCS module for implementation and create log files that are sent to the system management module.

### 2.2.5 Vehicle Control System (VCS) {#2.2.5-vehicle-control-system-(vcs)}

The VCS acts as the execution layer of the self-driving system, converting high-level driving commands into precise physical actions. It controls steering, acceleration, and braking by sending commands to the actuators of the vehicle. Additionally, the VCS implements the collision avoidance commands of the planning module, ensuring that corrective actions are taken when obstacles or hazardous conditions are detected. The VCS can also field commands directly through human input. These commands will supersede the commands sent by the planning module.

### 2.2.6 System Management {#2.2.6-system-management}

The system management module logs the overall operation of the self-driving system by collecting log files from the planning module. It also facilitates system performance analysis and automatic failover mechanisms to maintain system stability and reliability. The system management module can connect to the cloud to allow for data transfers, cloud uploading, and downloading.

### 2.2.7 Technical Interface {#2.2.7-technical-interface}

The Technical Interface Module acts as the bridge between the vehicle's internal systems, the driver, and the cloud infrastructure. It provides human-machine interaction functionalities, allowing the driver to receive system feedback and intervene when necessary. This module also ensures cloud connectivity for remote monitoring, data logging, and over-the-air (OTA) software updates.

### 2.2.8 Cloud {#2.2.8-cloud}

The Cloud Connectivity Module is a crucial part of the system’s IoT-based architecture, enabling remote diagnostics, data logging, over-the-air (OTA) updates, and system optimization. It ensures seamless integration between the vehicle’s onboard modules and external cloud services, providing real-time monitoring, data analytics, and predictive maintenance. The cloud features a physical interface that enables technicians to integrate it into system management. Once connected, the system management can transmit all relevant data to the cloud.

### 2.2.9 Driver Intervention {#2.2.9-driver-intervention}

The Driver Intervention module relates to the physical input by the car's driver that feeds directly into the VCS. This includes steering, braking, acceleration, turn signaling, and wiper control. The input will supersede the input of the planning module in the VCS. This module also implements nondriving functions such as air conditioning control, radio, and onboard entertainment.

## 2.3 Validity of Architecture {#2.3-validity-of-architecture}

### 2.3.1 Driver Assistance {#2.3.1-driver-assistance}

Driver assistance relies on robust architectures integrating sensors and cloud connectivity to ensure efficient vehicle operation. One example of driver assistance is Lane Keeping Assist (LKA). This system helps the vehicle stay centered in the lane when drifting is detected. It uses autonomous steering with the Lane Departure Warning System which notifies the driver. The car will have a set of cameras looking at the lines on the road. The cameras feed the data to the car’s computer, which interprets where the vehicle is positioned in relation to the lane. The computer can detect whether the vehicle is drifting closer or away from the lines, alerting the driver and self-correcting the vehicle. Driver input should only be done when needed. For example, turning on windshield wipers if the car does not automatically register it is raining.

### 2.3.2 Self-Driving Functionality {#2.3.2-self-driving-functionality}

Self-driving functionality uses sensor fusion to navigate roads autonomously and adjust speeds and steering based on real-time traffic data. The Society of Automotive Engineers has labeled six levels of automated driving, “ranging from full control of a vehicle by a physical driver, assisted by technology, to a vehicle that can operate without any on-board human input” (Garsten). Self-driving vehicles use three main electronics, radar, cameras, and laser-based LiDar, which stands for light detection and ranging. The radar, cameras, and a laser-based LiDar feed data to the vehicle’s processors using software, algorithms, and machine learning as well as send signals to the vehicle’s actuators to allow self-braking, steering, and acceleration. 

### 2.3.3 System Administration {#2.3.3-system-administration}

System admin involves managing and maintaining IT infrastructures, ensuring the vehicles are reliable, secure, and efficient. One example of this is cloud interface. This includes uploading driving performance data to the cloud as well as facilitating over-the-air (OTA) software updates to enhance functionality. Traditional software updates require a visit to a service center while OTA allows for easy deployment of patches, security fixes, and system updates. The vehicle is able to communicate with a cloud-based update server to download and verify software updates before installation. The system admin will also make sure the vehicle will not have any software updates the car is running.

# 3 Requirements {#3-requirements}

## 3.1 Functionality Requirements {#3.1-functionality-requirements}

The following requirements are for the functionality of each sub-routine of the car. The requirements, pre- and post-conditions, and all exceptions are contained in each routine within each of the requirements.

### 3.1.1 Car Start Requirement  {#3.1.1-car-start-requirement}

Pre-conditions

- Key is near the car within 5 feet from the door  
- Car is stationary

Post-condition 

- Driver display indicates car is on

Requirements 

1. Driver has pushed the on-key  
2. The “one-sensor” detects the request  
3. Sensor fusion receives the car-on request  
4. Sensor fusion sends requests to planning  
5. Planning verifies the request and if all conditions are met (such as battery level) sends that request to VCS  
6. VCS verifies information and starts the car  
7. Display indicates the car is on. 

Exception:

- Planning or VCS Deny Request and displays the denial

### 3.1.2 Forward Object Detection Requirements {#3.1.2-forward-object-detection-requirements}

The car shall identify objects in the forward position and send the correct information to planning for corrective action.

Pre-conditions:

- Car is moving forward  
- Front long range radar (LRR) detects an object in front of the driving path

Post-conditions:

- No danger  
- Object getting closer to the vehicle  
- Object getting further from the vehicle

Requirements:

1. Front LRR detects an object X feet in front of the car  
2. Sensor Fusion receives the radar data of the object at X fet and the car speed to send to Planning  
3. Planning computes the distance between the car and the object.  
   1. If X is increasing with time, then Planning ignores the input  
   2. If X is decreasing:  
      1. X \> 200’ planning ignores the request  
      2. X \<= 200’ it commands the VCS to apply brake and lower speed according to the table

| Distance From Object | Brake Level |
| :---- | :---- |
| Greater than 150 | Brake 1 |
| Greater than 100 | Brake 2 |
| Greater than 50 | Brake 3 |
| Less than 50 | Emergency Brake |

### 3.1.3 Road Signs and Traffic Signal Detection Requirements {#3.1.3-road-signs-and-traffic-signal-detection-requirements}

The car shall distinguish and identify all traffic signals and road signs that are recognized by the United States Department of Transportation.

Pre-conditions:

- Car is in “drive”  
- Front camera detected traffic signal or road sign

Post-conditions:

- Car changes conditions based on planning module decsion

Requirements:

1. Front camera detects traffic signal or road sign  
2. Data is transferred to perception module where it is identified and categorized based on the data from camera  
3. Traffic signal or road sign identification is passed onto planning who determines correct corrective action based on table  
4. Give correct command to VCS who will implement the commands

| Road Sign | Action | Traffic Signal | Action |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Stop Sign | Slowly bring car to stop before stop sign | Green Light | Continue into intersection |
| Speed Limit | Adjust top speed to match | Orange Light | Prepare to stop if position is 100 feet or more away, otherwise continue |
| Road Work Ahead | Reduce speed slightly and continue to monitor for more signs | Red Light | Slowly bring car to stop before stop line |

### 3.1.4 Auto-Navigation Requirements {#3.1.4-auto-navigation-requirements}

The car shall plan routes and be able to drive to inputed addresses by the driver.

Pre-conditions:

- Car is in “park”  
- Driver has input destination address into the cars navigation system  
- Car is started and running

Post-conditions:

- Car arrives at destination

Requirements:

1. Car calculates best route to destination from GPS and cloud data  
2. Car enters “drive” and begins to execute planned route to destination  
3. Car arrives at destination and parks/waits for driver commands

Exceptions:

- Car does not have enough range to travel to destination, nearest gas station or one on route is added to route  
- Destination is not a valid address

### 3.1.5 Data-Log Collection Requirements {#3.1.5-data-log-collection-requirements}

The car shall collect data logs for all data gathered and generated for each driving session. The data shall be stored locally in the system management module and uploaded to the cloud.

Pre-conditions:

- Data was collected  
- System management has sufficient storage capacity  
- Secure cloud connection available for data upload

Post-conditions:

- Collected data is stored in system management  
- Data successfully uploaded to the cloud for further analysis

Requirements:

1. Car logs all sensor data during each session  
2. The system timestamps all recorded data  
3. The system uploads data to the cloud

Exceptions:

- The car’s system can fail to upload the data because of insufficient storage or data corruption

### 3.1.6 Technical Interface Requirements {#3.1.6-technical-interface-requirements}

The technical interface module shall allow a certified technician to access all data-log file stored in the system management module via a technical interface.

Pre-conditions:

- Technician is certified and authorized  
- Data logs are available in the system management  
- The technical interface is operational

Post-conditions:

- Technician gains access to the requested data logs

Requirements:

1. The system provides a secure interface for technicians to access data logs  
2. Technician shall verify their credentials to the interface  
3. Interface allows filtering logs by timestamp  
4. Interface allows data export in a structured format

Exceptions:

- Unauthorized access is attempted  
- Data logs are corrupted or missing  
- Technical interface is unavailable or displays error message

### 3.1.7 Driver Intervention Requirements {#3.1.7-driver-intervention-requirements}

Driver shall always have the access to override the self driving commands of the vehicle to ensure safety.

Pre-conditions:

- Car is in self-driving mode  
- Driver is present and capable of intervention

Post-conditions:

- Driver successfully overrides the self-driving system  
- Vehicle responds immediately to driver’s input

Requirements:

1. Driver is able to manually override acceleration, braking, and steering at any time  
2. The system provides immediate control to the driver upon intervention  
3. Car notifies driver when the override is engaged, providing a haptic, visual, or auditory confirmation when an override is detected

Exceptions:

- Override system fails and car sends an emergency alert to driver  
- Driver override is engaged in an unsafe manner (ex. excessive speed)

### 3.1.8 Cloud Module Data Reading Requirements {#3.1.8-cloud-module-data-reading-requirements}

The cloud module provides authorized systems and personnel access to stored data logs for further processing, analysis, and reporting

Pre-conditions:

- Data logs have been successfully uploaded to the cloud  
- The requesting system or personnel has proper authentication and authorization  
- The cloud module is operational and accessible

Post-conditions:

- The requested data logs are retrieved and delivered to the requesting system or personnel

Requirements:

1. The cloud module allows authorized systems and users to retrieve data logs securely  
2. The system allows filtering logs by timestamp  
3. The cloud interface provides access logs to track who accessed which data and when  
4. The cloud module supports integration with external analytical tools for further processing.

Exceptions:

- Requested data log is unavailable or corrupted   
- Unauthorized access attempts is detected

### 3.1.9 Emergency Stop Requirements {#3.1.9-emergency-stop-requirements}

The car has an emergency stop mechanism that allows immediate cessation of autonomous operations in case of critical system failures or safety concerns

Pre-conditions:

- Car is in self-driving mode  
- System failure, obstacle detection, or manual intervention is triggered

Post-conditions:

- Car comes to a controlled stop safely

Requirements:

1. Car has a physical emergency stop button accessible to the drive  
2. The systems allows remote emergency stops through an authorized control interface  
3. The emergency stop function immediately halts the car in a controlled manner  
4. Car alerts passengers of the emergency stop via visual and auditory signals

Exceptions:

- The emergency stop is non-functional due to the no detection of obstacle or system malfunction

### 3.1.10 Autonomous Parking Requirements {#3.1.10-autonomous-parking-requirements}

The car has an autonomous parking capability for locating, maneuvering, and positioning itself into designated parking spaces

Pre-conditions:

- Car is within a parking facility or area  
- Driver or system command initiated the autonomous parking mode

Post-conditions:

- Car successfully parks within the designated space  
- The system confirms completion and disengages autonomous mode

Requirements:

1. The system detects and identify available parking spots using sensors  
2. Car autonomously maneuvers into a parking space without driver input  
3. The system provides real-time feedback to driver during parking process  
4. If obstacles are detected, the system adjusts its parking trajectory or abort if necessary  
5. The system notifies driver upon successful parking

Exceptions:

- No suitable parking spot is found while autonomous parking mode  
- Car is unable to park safely due to obstacles and notifies driver for input

## 3.2 Non-Functional Requirements  {#3.2-non-functional-requirements}

The following non-function requirements for the vehicle. The requirements, pre-conditions, post-conditions, and all exceptions are contained in each routine within each of the requirements.

### 3.2.1 Reliability Requirements {#3.2.1-reliability-requirements}

The system must ensure the vehicle’s continuous operation and safety under a variety of real-time normal and stress conditions. It must handle sensor failures, driver input, and system diagnostics to maintain reliability.

Pre-conditions:

- Vehicle is on and operational.  
- All functionalities of the car, including sensors, controls, and communication modules are functioning correctly.

Post-conditions:

- Vehicle maintains operations utilizing similar systems or data sources in the case of a system failure.  
- System logs reliability events and recoveries. 

Requirements:

1. Uptime of 99.99% during operation of vehicle.  
2. Redundant failover systems for core functionalities to ensure fail-safe operations.  
   1. A primary sensor failure will result in a switch to an alternative sensor autonomously.   
3. System Management Module is capable of logging reliability events and fail-safes.  
4. Manual intervention overrides automated commands through Sensor Fusion within 75 milliseconds.  
5. Emergency stop is physically accessible to driver, remotely accessible by admin, and may execute within 250 milliseconds of activation.

Exceptions:

- Extreme environmental factors that impair hardware functionalities.  
- Critical hardware failure beyond fail-safe measures.

### 3.2.2 Security Requirements {#3.2.2-security-requirements}

The system must be secure against cyber threats, data breaches, and unauthorized access to both physical capital and systems.

Pre-conditions:

- Vehicle is on and operational.  
- IoT Engine and cloud infrastructure are functioning correctly and active.  
- Secure authentication methods and encryption mechanisms are active.

Post-conditions:

- All unauthorized access attempts are logged, blocked, and reported to users.  
- Secure authentication mechanisms remain active. 

Requirements:

1. Technicians use multi-factor authentication (MFA) for access to vehicle and system diagnostics.  
2. Intrusion detection system (IDS) with real-time monitoring to detect intrusion attempts and raising alerts.  
3. Secure OTA updating to verify authenticated signatures and verifications before installations.  
4. Data transmissions occur using end-to-end encryption (TLS 1.3) for all vehicle-to-cloud communications.  
5. No external devices can modify the VCS, access data or transmit information without the outlined authentication mechanisms within this requirement.

Exceptions:

- Unexpected cloud connectivity loss preventing remote security updates.  
- Zero-day exploits.

### 3.2.3 Performance Requirements {#3.2.3-performance-requirements}

The system must maintain real-time responses and availability to efficiently carry-out operations smoothly.

Pre-conditions:

- Vehicle is on and operational.  
- All functionalities of the car, including IoT Engine, sensors, and VCS are functioning correctly and active.  
- Cloud-based processing is available.

Post-conditions:

- Vehicle maintains real-time responses to sensor inputs.  
- Vehicle trajectory and location in real-space must be continuously updated. 

Requirements:

1. The Sensor Fusion Module must have a sensor data processing latency within 50 milliseconds.  
2. The Planning Module must execute critical decisions within 100 milliseconds after receiving Sensor Fusion input.  
3. Cloud-based decision latency must be within 1 second for all non-critical decisions.  
4. System must continue local logging if cloud connection is temporarily lost until it is regained and active.  
5. The vehicle must be fully operational 10 seconds after start up.  
6. Emergency braking must engage within 250 milliseconds of hazard detection.

Exceptions:

- Unexpected delays in data transmission from cloud services.  
- Temporary system shutdowns. 

### 3.2.4 Scalability Requirements {#3.2.4-scalability-requirements}

The system must be capable of scaling for expansion of vehicle uptake, additional sensors, and change in cloud-based services. 

Pre-conditions:

- IoT Engine is functioning correctly and actively able to handle an uptake in data flow.  
- Cloud infrastructure must support multiple vehicle instances.

Post-conditions:

- New additions integrate without requiring significant architectural changes.  
- Performance degradation does not exceed 5% when scaling. 

Requirements:

1. Support up to 100,000 vehicle connections in the cloud and 10,000+ vehicles uploading data to the cloud at once.  
2. Cloud infrastructure must dynamically support 10TB+ of new driving data per month.  
3. Cloud connectivity latency should not exceed 5% degradation when scaling.  
4. Cloud infrastructure for diagnostics must be able to support 100+ technicians at once.

Exceptions:

- Hardware limitations.  
- Unexpected delays caused by high network traffic.

### 3.2.5 Maintenance Requirements {#3.2.5-maintenance-requirements}

The system must be able to support updates, error logging, and long-term maintenance of systems.

Pre-conditions:

- IoT Engine is functioning correctly and actively able to handle an uptake in data flow.  
- The cloud infrastructure is functional and capable of supporting vehicle instances.  
- The vehicle is in an idle or non-critical state to perform maintenance tasks.

Post-conditions:

- Software updates are successfully applied without interrupting critical functions.  
- System logs are stored and retrievable for at least 90 days.  
- Technicals have continuous remote access for diagnostics and maintenance. 

Requirements:

1. Software updates must be OTA and without manual intervention 95% of the time.  
2. Software updates should not exceed 15 minutes.  
3. The System Management Module should store 90+ days of log data.  
4. Technician Interface must supply 24/7 remote access for logs and diagnostics.

Exceptions:

- Hardware limitations prevent certain updates from being installed.  
- Network disruptions delay or prevent OTA updates.  
- Insufficient storage space for log retention.   
- Unexpected cloud service downtime impacting remote diagnostics. 

### 3.2.6 Portability Requirements {#3.2.6-portability-requirements}

The system must be designed to support deployment across different vehicle models and hardware configurations without significant rework. 

Pre-conditions: 

- The core software architecture is modular and hardware-agnostic.  
- The system is designed to support varying vehicle specifications.   
- The cloud infrastructure can accommodate different vehicle configurations. 

Post-conditions: 

- The software can be deployed across multiple vehicle models with minimal modification.   
- Vehicle performance is not degraded due to software portability.   
- All core functionalities remain intact regardless of hardware differences 

Requirements: 

1. The software must be compatible with multiple hardware configurations, including different sensor types and processors.  
2. Modular design to allow easy integration of new components and upgrades.  
3. Standardized communication protocols for seamless data exchange between different vehicle models  
4. Support for multiple operating systems where applicable   
5. Ability to deploy updates remotely without requiring complete system redesign. 

Exceptions:  

- Hardware constraints preventing full compatibility.  
- Software dependencies that require modification for certain vehicle models.   
- Performance limitations due to differences in computing power across platforms. 

### 3.2.7 Reusability Requirements {#3.2.7-reusability-requirements}

The system must be designed with reusable components to facilitate efficient development, reduce costs, and enable the use of core modules in different applications. 

Pre-conditions: 

- The system is built using a modular and well-documented codebase.   
- Core functionalities are designed to be independent and reusable.   
- The software architecture supports reusability across different vehicle models and software projects. 

Post-conditions: 

- Modules can be reused in other autonomous vehicle applications without significant modification.   
- Code reusability reduces development time and maintenance costs.   
- System components remain maintainable and scalable. 

Requirements: 

1. The software must implement modular architecture with reusable components for different vehicle models.   
2. APIs and interfaces should be standardized to facilitate component reuse.   
3. Documentation must clearly define reusable components and their dependencies.   
4. Common functions (e.g., sensor fusion, localization, and path planning) should be designed for reuse across multiple projects. 

Expectations: 

- Specific hardware-dependent modules may require customization.   
- Certain features may not be fully reusable due to regulatory or performance constraints.  
- Updates or optimizations for one vehicle model may not be directly applicable to another without adaptation.
